"# Chapter 14 — Assembly, then higher — from opcodes to Scheme

Chapter 12 gave us a CPU that runs bytes. A program in that CPU is a
sequence of numbers: `1 0 5 1 1 3 3 0 1 7`. Nobody wants to write
programs like that. It is unreadable and one wrong number turns your
program into a random-number generator.

So humans build layers. Each layer trades a little bit of machine
directness for a lot of human clarity. This chapter walks the tower
of abstractions, from machine code at the bottom up to Motoi Scheme
at the top.

## Machine code

At the bottom is what the CPU reads. Bytes. Numbers. That is what
chapter 12's little CPU executed. It is the only thing the CPU
understands. Every layer above it is translated back down to this,
eventually, before anything happens.

Machine code is:

- Unreadable to humans.
- Compact.
- Architecture-specific (6502 machine code doesn't run on ARM).
- What every processor on Earth ultimately executes.

## Assembly language

The first layer up is **assembly language.** Assembly is a one-to-one
textual encoding of machine code. Each instruction has a mnemonic
name and named registers. An **assembler** is a small program that
translates the text into bytes.

For our tiny CPU, assembly might look like:

```
        LDI  R0, 5
        LDI  R1, 3
        ADD  R0, R1
        HALT
```

That is the exact same program as the `1 0 5 1 1 3 3 0 1 7` byte
sequence from chapter 12, but readable. Every instruction maps to
exactly one machine instruction.

Assembly still has real hardware in view — you know exactly what
each instruction does. But you don't have to hex-edit anything. You
type mnemonics and labels, run the assembler, and get machine code.

## The assembler is a program

An assembler is a table lookup plus a symbol table for labels. For our
tiny CPU, we can write a tiny assembler in Motoi Scheme:

```
(define opcodes
  '((NOP  0 0)      ;; opcode, operand count
    (LDI  1 2)
    (MOV  2 2)
    (ADD  3 2)
    (SUB  4 2)
    (JMP  5 1)
    (JZ   6 1)
    (HALT 7 0)))

(define (opcode-lookup name)
  (cond
    ((null? opcodes) (error 'unknown-mnemonic name))
    ((assv name opcodes) => cadr)
    (else (error 'unknown-mnemonic name))))

(define (assemble source)
  ;; source is a list like ((LDI R0 5) (LDI R1 3) (ADD R0 R1) (HALT))
  (let loop ((remaining source) (bytes '()))
    (if (null? remaining)
        (reverse bytes)
        (let* ((instr (car remaining))
               (mnem  (car instr))
               (args  (cdr instr))
               (op    (opcode-lookup mnem))
               (numeric-args
                (map (lambda (a)
                       (cond
                         ((number? a) a)
                         ((symbol? a)
                          ;; register R0..R3 -> 0..3
                          (case a ((R0) 0) ((R1) 1) ((R2) 2) ((R3) 3)
                                  (else (error 'unknown-symbol a))))))
                     args)))
          (loop (cdr remaining)
                (append (reverse numeric-args)
                        (cons op bytes)))))))

(assemble '((LDI R0 5) (LDI R1 3) (ADD R0 R1) (HALT)))
;; => (1 0 5 1 1 3 3 0 1 7)
```

Same bytes as before, but from assembly source. That is what real
assemblers do (in about ten thousand times as many lines of code to
handle all the edge cases).

## The tower of C

Assembly is nice, but it is still per-architecture, and you have to
manage registers by hand. In 1972, Dennis Ritchie at Bell Labs wrote
a language called **C** to write the Unix operating system in. C was
the first widely successful **portable systems language.**

C's promise: you write once, compile to whatever CPU you want, and
the compiler figures out register allocation and calling conventions.
`x + y` in C is still an ADD in the machine code, but you don't have
to say which registers to use.

C is close enough to the machine that you can predict roughly what
assembly it will produce, but high enough that a program written for
the PDP-11 in 1975 can be recompiled for a modern ARM in 2026 without
changes. That is a fifty-year hold on portability. Very few
inventions in software have aged so well.

C is why Unix, Linux, the BSDs, most operating system kernels, and
much of the runtime of every language you use are written in C or
its descendant C++.

## The tower of Lisp

In 1958, John McCarthy at MIT invented **Lisp** — the second-oldest
high-level programming language still in use (after Fortran). Lisp
was designed for symbolic computation, not systems programming. It
was a very different vision.

McCarthy's key insight: **program is data.** In Lisp, a program is a
list of symbols. `(+ 1 2)` is both a program that adds one and two
and a list of three symbols that you can inspect, modify, or generate.

That symmetry lets Lisp programs write Lisp programs. **Macros**
extend the language from within the language. **The `eval` function**
takes a data structure and runs it as a program. It is a completely
different style from C's \"generate a fixed machine code image\" model.

Guy Steele and Gerald Sussman published **Scheme** in 1975 as a
minimalist Lisp dialect at MIT. Scheme cleaned up Lisp's variable
scoping (lexical, not dynamic — a big win) and formalised the
lambda calculus at the core.

Motoi Scheme is a direct descendant of that 1975 Scheme, through the
IEEE and R7RS standards. When you type `(+ 1 2)` into the Motoi REPL,
you are typing something that would be recognised, in 1975, by
McCarthy, Steele, and Sussman.

## The stack of interpreters

Motoi Scheme is an interpreter. When you type an expression, the
interpreter:

1. **Reads** the text into a data structure (a nested list).
2. **Evaluates** the data structure, walking it recursively.
3. **Prints** the result.

That is the classic REPL: Read-Eval-Print Loop. It is a loop (chapter
10). It is a state machine (chapter 10 again). The state includes
the environment (variable bindings).

The interpreter itself is written in JavaScript (Motoi is a JS
implementation of a Scheme). The JavaScript engine (V8, SpiderMonkey,
JavaScriptCore) is a just-in-time compiler that translates JS into
machine code. That machine code runs on your CPU. Your CPU is the
one from chapter 12, just much bigger.

Layers, from bottom to top:

```
   CPU hardware (transistors, chapter 4)
      running
   machine code (chapter 12)
      generated by
   the JavaScript JIT
      running
   the Motoi Scheme interpreter (JavaScript)
      evaluating
   Motoi Scheme code (what you type)
```

Five or six layers of abstraction, each one built by humans, each
one running the layer above it, each one grounded ultimately in
Boolean logic and gates.

That is the **tower of abstractions.** Every programmer works
somewhere on that tower. Some (kernel hackers, chip designers) work
near the bottom. Some (data scientists, web developers) work near
the top. Motoi is a language you can use anywhere on the tower, but
he lives around the Scheme layer.

## Motoi's reader

Motoi's reader is a small program that reads text and produces
`cons` cells. That is meta. The reader converts text into the same
data structure Scheme programs are made of. Then the interpreter
walks the data structure.

Sketch:

```
(define (motoi-read text)
  ;; skips whitespace, reads tokens, builds nested lists
  ;; the actual reader in Motoi's source is in src/reader.js
  ...)

(motoi-read \"(+ 1 2)\")
;; => (+ 1 2)   ;; a list of three symbols

(motoi-read \"(define (square x) (* x x))\")
;; => (define (square x) (* x x))
```

The output of the reader is the input to the evaluator. The evaluator
recurses on the list structure:

```
(define (motoi-eval expr env)
  (cond
    ((number? expr)  expr)
    ((symbol? expr)  (lookup expr env))
    ((pair? expr)
     (let ((op (car expr)) (args (cdr expr)))
       (cond
         ((eq? op 'quote)  (car args))
         ((eq? op 'if)     (if (motoi-eval (car args) env)
                               (motoi-eval (cadr args) env)
                               (motoi-eval (caddr args) env)))
         ((eq? op 'lambda) (make-closure args env))
         (else
          ;; apply
          (let ((f    (motoi-eval op env))
                (vals (map (lambda (a) (motoi-eval a env)) args)))
            (apply-closure f vals))))))))
```

That is the shape of every interpreter for every language. Type-check
the expression, dispatch on its kind, recurse. Motoi Scheme's actual
evaluator is more polished (tail calls, macros, environments), but
this is the shape.

## SICP

Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs by Harold Abelson,
Gerald Jay Sussman, and Julie Sussman (MIT Press, first edition 1985)
is the classic textbook for exactly this material. It builds Scheme
in Scheme, an interpreter in the language it interprets. It is what
Motoi wishes he had been in a lab with when he was younger.

Read SICP after this book. It is Appendix G's number one
recommendation for anyone who wants to go deeper into interpreters,
compilers, and the tower of abstractions. Chapter 4 of SICP builds
an interpreter for Scheme in Scheme. Chapter 5 builds a compiler.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

- Everything above machine code is a **tower of translations.**
- Each layer trades some machine directness for some human clarity.
- The layers are grounded in gates, adders, memory, and the CPU
  loop, no matter how high they go.
- Scheme sits fairly high on the tower — it is close to the way
  humans think about mathematics and less close to the way the CPU
  works. Which is why interpreting Scheme is slower than executing
  C, and executing C is slower than executing hand-tuned assembly,
  and executing assembly is slower than executing a custom silicon
  circuit that does the exact same thing.

Portability, clarity, and safety go up as you climb the tower. Peak
performance and control go up as you climb down. Motoi picks a rung
in the middle. So do most working programmers.

## The loop appears

The REPL is a loop. The interpreter walks recursive expressions,
which are loops. The JIT compiler has an optimization loop. The CPU
has the fetch-decode-execute loop. Every layer of the tower has a
loop somewhere. Loops are how machines do anything at all. See
Appendix E.

## Next

Chapter 15: operating systems and networks. Machines cooperating
across cables, across rooms, across oceans.
")
